SIMPLE: retain
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Retain
<hw>Re*tain"</hw> <pr>(r⟦esl⟧*t⟦amac⟧n")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Retained</conjf>
<pr>(r⟦esl⟧*t⟦amac⟧nd")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Retaining</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>retainir</ets>, L.
<ets>retinere</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>tenere</ets> to
hold, keep. See <er>Tenable</er>, and cf. <er>Rein</er> of a bridle,
<er>Retention</er>, <er>Retinue</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To
continue to hold; to keep in possession; not to lose, part with, or
dismiss; to restrain from departure, escape, or the like.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧Thy shape invisible <xex>retain</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be obedient, and <qex>retain</qex>⟦br⟧
Unalterably firm his love entire.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An executor may <qex>retain</qex> a debt due to him from the
testator.</q> <rj><qau>Blackstone.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To keep in pay; to employ by a preliminary fee paid;
to hire; to engage; <as>as, to <ex>retain</ex> a
counselor</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A Benedictine convent has now <qex>retained</qex> the most learned
father of their order to write in its defense.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To restrain; to prevent.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Sir W. Temple.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Retaining wall</b></col> <fld>(Arch. & Engin.)</fld>,
<cd>a wall built to keep any movable backing, or a bank of sand or
earth, in its place; -- called also <altname>retain
wall</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To keep; hold; restrain. See
<er>Keep</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retain</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Retain
<hw>Re*tain"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To belong; to
pertain.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A somewhat languid relish, <qex>retaining</qex> to bitterness.</q>
<rj><qau>Boyle.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To keep; to continue; to remain.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Donne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retainable</ent>⟦br⟧
